dataIdInfo.idAbs: LAGOS-NE contains data for all 51,102 lakes and reservoirs > 4 ha in the 17 U.S. state study area and along their borders (1,800,000 sq. km.), referred to as the census lake population. The LAGOS-NE GIS Database complements three data modules called LAGOS-NE-LOCUS, LAGOS-NE-GEO, and LAGOS-NE-LIMNO. The LAGOS-NE GIS Database contains geospatial data layers describing the boundaries, spatial classifications, and freshwater features used to compile the LAGOS-NE database. The LAGOS-NE IWS layer contains interlake watershed polygons for all of the LAGOS-NE lakes greater than or equal to 4 hectares. The watershed delineations were performed with an automated process custom to LAGOS-NE and are defined as follows: The area of land that drains directly into a lake, and into all upstream-connected, permanent streams to that lake exclusive of any upstream lake watersheds for lakes ? 10 ha that are connected via permanent streams.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: We have created a database for lakes in the northeastern-most 17 U.S. states called LAGOS-NE (LAke multi-scaled GeOSpatial and temporal database). We had three related motivations for developing this database: (1) to develop the basic understanding of lake nutrients and productivity at sub-continental scales, with a focus on studying cross-scale interactions and their drivers using water quality data on thousands of lakes collected overacross the last several decades (see Soranno et al. 2014 and Soranno et al. 2015 for details); (2) to build the capacity to apply this scientific understanding to environmental management and policy of freshwaters; and, (3) to foster broad-scale research by designing an open-science database infrastructure that includes detailed characterization of lake ecological context that is extensible for future uses and by making the data and methods publicly accessible. The LAGOS-NE GIS Database is provided for the purposes of displaying LAGOS-NE data, understanding their geospatial relationships, and supporting further spatial analyses with these data. The LAGOS-NE IWS layer identifies watersheds for the purpose of studying the influence of ecological context on lake nutrients and water quality.

prcStep.stepDesc: The complete documentation of the process is found in Soranno et al. (2015), Supplemental File 8, located at http://dx.doi.org/10.1186/s13742-015-0067-4. The major steps in the watershed delineation process are as follows: 1) Obtain and mosaic NED DEMs, NHD data. Introduce 'walls' that prevent flow from crossing HU8 boundaries. Data is projected here to USGS Albers coordinate system, and later as necessary. 2) DEM conditioning: Burn NHD flowlines (streams, and more*) into DEM using AGREE-like conditioning. This step ensures that flow accumulates into cells that correspond with the NHD flowlines. 3) DEM conditioning: Fill pits in the DEM. This step prevents flow from accumulating in isolated pits (Jenson and Domingue 1988). 4) Force the flow to not cross HU8 boundaries by adding 'walls' along the boundary. 5) Calculate D8 flow direction from the DEM. 6) Select pour points: All NHD flowlines and lakes meeting the size threshold and being of certain FCodes (non-intermittent lakes and reservoirs) are included. Lakes take precedence where lakes and flowlines (in particular, artificial paths through lakes) overlap. 7) Calculate watersheds from the flow direction rasters using the selected pour points. 8) Remove watersheds smaller than 1ha and those that do not intersect the NHD flowlines or selected lakes. Use a 'nibble' algorithm to partition the areas where watersheds were removed into the retained watersheds. 9) Ensure that watershed polygons do not cross HU8 boundaries and that the lakes are perfectly nested within their own watersheds. 10) Aggregate watersheds. An aggregated watershed is created for each eligible lake in the NHD. The lake itself is erased from the watershed polygon and any remaining holes smaller than 3.9 ha are filled in. a. 'Interlake watersheds': All of the watersheds corresponding to network elements (lakes/streams) upstream of any eligible lake are merged until a 10-hectare lake is reached in the network, and no watersheds including and beyond the 10-hectare lake are included. b. 'Cumulative watersheds': All watersheds corresponding to network elements (lakes/streams) upstream of any eligible lake are merged until the HU8 boundary prevents any additional watersheds from being included. The lake itself is erased from the watershed polygon and any remaining holes smaller than 3.9 ha are filled in.

dataSource.srcDesc: The water bodies (NHDWaterbody), flow lines (NHDFlowline), and flow network (HYDRO_NET) used as inputs for the watershed delineation. The WBD_HU8 layer packaged with the NHD was used for walls restraining the flow.
